Investment and Trading Capstone Project: Build a Stock Price Indicator¶

This project consists of two main parts:

1. build a stock predictor user interface
The stock predictor firstly asks the user to input: stocks we are interested in, a certain date range (training start date, training end date), a prediction interval (number of trading days), and a query date. Then it outputs the predicted future Adjusted Close prices of the stocks for the user. The framework of the interface is as follows.

  • The interface firstly asks users to input a training start date, a training end date and a list of stock symbols (e.g. GOOG, AAPL). The interface will ask users to choose a positive integer from 1, 5, 10 and 20. The integer indicates the prediction interval in terms of trading days. For example, choosing prediction interval 5 means that the user want the interface to predict the Adjusted Closes price of the day that is 5 trading days after the query date.

  • According to the input, the daily trading data of the stocks and S&P 500 ranging from the training start date to the training end date are extracted directly from the Yahoo! Finance by the API of python module pandas_datareader.data. Since the project is to predict Adjusted Close prices, we extract the Adjusted Close prices from the raw data. These works can be done by the function get_data() described in section 1.1.

  • Some technical indicators such as Bollinger Bond Value, Relative Strengh Index and so on are computed based on the Adjusted Close data. For each stock of interest, 18 technical indicators are computed, and they will be used as input features in our regression models. The target value of our regression models is the rate (in percentage) that the price will change at the future date corresponds to the prediction interval. The target value is also computed based on the Adjusted Close data. The features and corresponding target value are combined to form the training data. These works can by done by the function process_data() function in section 1.1. Both get_data() and process_data() functions are included in file DataGetter.py.

  • Regression methods including KNN, Bagging, Decision Tree and Random Forest are applied on the training data. Decision Tree and Random Forest methods are from the sci-kit learn module. KNN and Bagging methods are implemented by myself. They are described in section 1.2. During the model fitting process, each method attempts different choices of tuning parameters. All the models are evaluated in the training phase, and the best model is selected as the final model of the predictor interface. Specifically, we firstly divide the training data into two parts: a smaller training data set (75%) and a validation data set (25%). Then the smaller training data set is used to fit regression models, each of which attempts different tuning paramters. These models' performance then are evaluated on the validation data set, and the best method and corresponding optimal choice of the tuning parameter are selected. Finally, we use the whole training data set to fit a regression model using the best method and its corresponding optimal choice of tuning parameter. And this model will be used as the final model in the predictor system. These works are done by the methods of BestLearner class.

  • After the final model is obtained, the user interface will ask the user to input a query date. The features at the query date will be computed and used to predict the rate of change of the stocks. Then the predictions of each stock's future price is computed based on its price at the query date and its predicted rate of change. The interface then output the predictions.

All the above works are combined in the class StockIndicator, which is included in the file StockIndicator.py. The code for the user interface consists of DataGetter.py, KNN.py, BagLearner.py, BestLearner.py and StockIndicator.py. The interface can be run under Ubuntu 14.04 by typing "python StockIndicator.py" in the terminal. The interface can also be run in this notebook. The details will be illustrated in the section 1.

2. case studies based on the stock predictor
Three case studies are conducted to evaluate the stock predictor we built in part 1. They are:

  • Google: training date range: 01/01/2011-12/31/2014, testing date range: 01/01/2015-12/31/2015
  • Apple: training date range: 01/01/2003-12/31/2007, testing date range: 01/01/2008-12/31/2008
  • IBM: training date range: 01/01/2010-12/31/2013, testing date range: 01/01/2014-12/31/2014

In each case study, a stock predictor is built using the data of training date range. Then the predictor is tested on the data of testing date range. The mean absolute percentage error (MAPE) is used as the metrics to evaluate the performance of the predictor. We also construct a trading strategy based on the predictions given by the predictor. The trading strategy is then used to trade the stock on the testing date range, and the portfolio values are computed. To evaluate the trading strategy, the cumulative return and Sharpe ratio on the portfolio values will be computed. Also, we will use the stock prices during the testing date range as the benchmark to compare with the portfolio values. These works are all implemented in the class TradeStock. The trading strategy is implemented in the method create_orders(). The method create_results() generates the results of the study.

The code for case studies is included in file TradingStrategy.py. By typing "python TradingStrategy.py" in the terminal, the results of the studies shown in the report will be generated. The explanation of the code will be illustrated in the later part of this notebook. Also, the results and plots that shown in the report will also be generated and explained in the notebook.

1. Build a stock predictor user interface¶

1.1 Extract Stock Price Data and Pre-process Data¶

get_data() and process_data() functions are included in DataGetter.py file.

The function get_data() takes stock symbols (symbols) and a training start date (train_sd) as input arguments. Then the function extracts daily Adujusted Close price data of the stocks and S&P 500 from Yahoo! Finance. The extracted price data are ranging from the training start date (train_sd) to present day. The function returns the extracted data as a dataframe.

The data are extracted from Yahoo Finance through the API pandas_datareader.data, which has been imported as web at the beginning of the notebook.

Also, the output data frame not only includes the price of the input stocks, but also includes the price of the S&P 500, which has the column name "SPY" in the output data frame. The reason for including the "SPY" price is tha we also want the technical indicators generated from "SPY" price to be the input features of our regression models.

The detail of the get_data() function is shown as follows:

In [2]:
def get_data(symbols, train_sd, data_source = "yahoo"):

    """
    The function takes some stock symbols and a training start date as input, 
        and extracts close prices data of these symbols and SPY from yahoo finance, 
        ranging from the specified training start date to present day.

    @param symbols:  a list, symbols to extract from yahoo finance
    @param train_sd: a datetime object, training data start date  
    @return:         a dataframe containing adjusted close prices of the symbols 
                     and SPY from train_sd to present
    """
    
    if "SPY" not in symbols:
        symbols = symbols + ["SPY"]

    df = web.DataReader(name=symbols[0], data_source=data_source, start=train_sd)[["Adj Close"]]
    #use double [[]] returns a DataFrame, not a Series
    df = df.rename(columns={"Adj Close": symbols[0]})

    for i in range(1, len(symbols)):
        df_temp = web.DataReader(name=symbols[i], data_source=data_source, start=train_sd)[["Adj Close"]]
        df_temp = df_temp.rename(columns={"Adj Close": symbols[i]})
        df = df.join(df_temp)

    df = df.dropna(subset=["SPY"])

    return df

The process_data() function computes technical indicators based on the daily Adjusted Close prices obtained by get_data() function, and the rate of future change of the stock corresponds to the input prediction interval. The technical indicators and the rate of change are then combined to a dataframe. The dataframe is then divided to two parts by the input training end date. The two dataframes are then returned.

The input arguments of the the function include a dataframe (df_allprices) containing Ajusted Close prices of stocks and S&P 500, a stock symbol (symbol), the training end date (train_ed), and the prediction interval (n_days). The function will extract the stock price of the input stock (symbol) from the input dataframe (df_allprices), and then generate 18 technical indicators which will be used as features in regression models. The technical indicators include:

  1. Billinger Bonds values for 5, 10 and 20 trading days of the stock price respectively
  2. Billinger Bonds values for 5, 10 and 20 trading days of the S&P 500 respectively
  3. Rate of Change of the stock's price for the past 5, 10 and 20 trading days respectively
  4. Rate of Change of S&P 500 for the past 5, 10 and 20 trading days respectively
  5. RSI values for 5, 10 and 20 trading days of the stock price respectively
  6. RSI values for 5, 10 and 20 trading days of the SP&P 500

The function also compute the rate of future change of the stock corresponds to the input prediction interval (n_days). For example, if we input n_days=5, then the rate of changes of the stock price 5 trading days later will be computed. The rate of change will be used as target variable in the regression models. Besides, the stock price and the future actual stock price are also included in the output data frames for the use of model evaluations in the future case studies.

The function returns two data frames: training data frame and testing data frame. Both data frames contain technical indicators of the input symbol and SPY as columns. Also, the rate of change, stock price and future actual stock price are included in the data frames as columns. The training data frame have the date range from the training start date to the training end date. The testing data frame has the date range from the day after the training end date to present day.

The code of the funcion is:

def process_data(df_allprices, symbol, train_ed, n_days):
    """
    The function computes technical indicators based on the prices data obtained by get_data() function, 
        and returns training set and testing set of a specified symbol.
    The returned training and testing set are dataframes that contain technical indicators as columns.
    The returned dataframes also contains rate of change as target variable, stock prices and future actual stock prices.
    The indicators contains: Billinger Bonds values for 5, 10 and 20 trading days of the symbol's prices
                             Billinger Bonds values for 5, 10 and 20 trading days of the SPY prices
                             Rate of Change values for the past 5, 10 and 20 trading days of the symbol's prices
                             Rate of Change values for the past 5, 10 and 20 trading days of the SPY prices
                             RSI values for 5, 10 and 20 trading days of the symbol's prices
                             RSI values for 5, 10 and 20 trading days of the SPY prices
    The input n_days denotes the prediction interval, 
        e.g. n_days=5 means you want to predict the stock price at the day that is 5 trading days later.

    @param df_allprices: dataframe, adj close of all symbols and SPY 
    @param symbol:       str, the symbol to process 
    @param train_ed:     datetime object, training end date 
    @param n_days:       int, prediction interval, e.g. n_days=5 means you want to 
                         predict the stock price 5 trading days later.
    return: two dataframes with stock indicators of symbol and SPY
            Dataframes also contains rate of change as target variable (Y).
            Dataframes also contains stock prices and future stock prices.
            Two dataframs are training and testing sets respectively.
    """
    
    ans_df = pd.DataFrame(index=df_allprices.index) #initialize the output data frame 
    df_symbol = df_allprices[symbol] #extract the stock price of the input symbol from df_allprices
    df_SPY = df_allprices["SPY"] #extract the SPY price from df_allprices
    
    #compute Billinger Bond values for 5 trading days of the symbol's stock price
    sma_5 = pd.Series.rolling(df_symbol, window=5, center=False).mean()
    std_5 = pd.Series.rolling(df_symbol, window=5, center=False).std()
    bb_5 = (df_symbol - sma_5) / (2 * std_5)
    ans_df["BB_5"] = bb_5
    
    #compute Billinger Bond values for 10 trading days of the symbol's stock price
    sma_10 = pd.Series.rolling(df_symbol, window=10, center=False).mean()
    std_10 = pd.Series.rolling(df_symbol, window=10, center=False).std()
    bb_10 = (df_symbol - sma_10) / (2 * std_10)
    ans_df["BB_10"] = bb_10
    
    #compute Billinger Bond values for 20 trading days of the symbol's stock price
    sma_20 = pd.Series.rolling(df_symbol, window=20, center=False).mean()
    std_20 = pd.Series.rolling(df_symbol, window=20, center=False).std()
    bb_20 = (df_symbol - sma_20) / (2 * std_20)
    ans_df["BB_20"] = bb_20
    
    #compute Billinger Bond values for 5 trading days of SPY price
    sma_5_SPY = pd.Series.rolling(df_SPY, window=5, center=False).mean()
    std_5_SPY = pd.Series.rolling(df_SPY, window=5, center=False).std()
    bb_5_SPY = (df_SPY - sma_5_SPY) / (2 * std_5_SPY)
    ans_df["BB_5_SPY"] = bb_5_SPY
    
    #compute Billinger Bond values for 10 trading days of SPY price
    sma_10_SPY= pd.Series.rolling(df_SPY, window=10, center=False).mean()
    std_10_SPY = pd.Series.rolling(df_SPY, window=10, center=False).std()
    bb_10_SPY = (df_SPY - sma_10_SPY) / (2 * std_10_SPY)
    ans_df["BB_10_SPY"] = bb_10_SPY
    
    #compute Billinger Bond values for 20 trading days of SPY price
    sma_20_SPY= pd.Series.rolling(df_SPY, window=20, center=False).mean()
    std_20_SPY = pd.Series.rolling(df_SPY, window=20, center=False).std()
    bb_20_SPY = (df_SPY - sma_20_SPY) / (2 * std_20_SPY)
    ans_df["BB_20_SPY"] = bb_20_SPY
    
    # compute rate of change in stock price of the symbol for the past 5 trading days
    roc_5 = df_symbol[5:]/df_symbol[:-5].values - 1
    ans_df["ROC_5"] = roc_5
    
    # compute rate of change in stock price of the symbol for the past 10 trading days
    roc_10 = df_symbol[10:]/df_symbol[:-10].values - 1
    ans_df["ROC_10"] = roc_10
    
    # compute rate of change in stock price of the symbol for the past 20 trading days
    roc_20 = df_symbol[20:]/df_symbol[:-20].values - 1
    ans_df["ROC_20"] = roc_20
    
    # compute rate of change in SPY price for the past 5 trading days
    roc_5_SPY = df_SPY[5:]/df_SPY[:-5].values - 1
    ans_df["ROC_5_SPY"] = roc_5_SPY
    
    # compute rate of change in SPY price for the past 10 traing days
    roc_10_SPY = df_SPY[10:]/df_SPY[:-10].values - 1
    ans_df["ROC_10_SPY"] = roc_10_SPY
    
    # compute rate of change in SPY price for the past 20 trading days
    roc_20_SPY = df_SPY[20:]/df_SPY[:-20].values - 1
    ans_df["ROC_20_SPY"] = roc_20_SPY
    
    # compute RSI indicator of symbol's price
    delta = df_symbol.diff()
    up, down = delta.copy(), delta.copy()
    up[up < 0] = 0
    down[down > 0] = 0
    
    # RSI of the symbol's price for 5 trading days
    up_5 = pd.Series.rolling(up, window=5, center=False).mean()
    down_5 = pd.Series.rolling(down.abs(), window=5, center=False).mean()
    RS_5 = up_5 / down_5
    RSI_5 = 100.0 - (100.0 / (1.0 + RS_5))
    ans_df["RSI_5"] = RSI_5
    
    # RSI of the symbol's price for 10 trading days
    up_10 = pd.Series.rolling(up, window=10, center=False).mean()
    down_10 = pd.Series.rolling(down.abs(), window=10, center=False).mean()
    RS_10 = up_10 / down_10
    RSI_10 = 100.0 - (100.0 / (1.0 + RS_10))
    ans_df["RSI_10"] = RSI_10
    
    # RSI of the symbol's price for 20 trading days
    up_20 = pd.Series.rolling(up, window=20, center=False).mean()
    down_20 = pd.Series.rolling(down.abs(), window=20, center=False).mean()
    RS_20 = up_20 / down_20
    RSI_20 = 100.0 - (100.0 / (1.0 + RS_20))
    ans_df["RSI_20"] = RSI_20
    
    # compute RSI of SPY
    delta_SPY = df_SPY.diff()
    up_SPY, down_SPY = delta_SPY.copy(), delta_SPY.copy()
    up_SPY[up_SPY < 0] = 0
    down_SPY[down_SPY > 0] = 0
    
    # compute RSI of SPY for 5 days
    up_5_SPY = pd.Series.rolling(up_SPY, window=5, center=False).mean()
    down_5_SPY = pd.Series.rolling(down_SPY.abs(), window=5, center=False).mean()
    RS_5_SPY = up_5_SPY / down_5_SPY
    RSI_5_SPY = 100.0 - (100.0 / (1.0 + RS_5_SPY))
    ans_df["RSI_5_SPY"] = RSI_5_SPY
    
    # compute RSI of SPY for 10 days
    up_10_SPY = pd.Series.rolling(up_SPY, window=10, center=False).mean()
    down_10_SPY = pd.Series.rolling(down_SPY.abs(), window=10, center=False).mean()
    RS_10_SPY = up_10_SPY / down_10_SPY
    RSI_10_SPY = 100.0 - (100.0 / (1.0 + RS_10_SPY))
    ans_df["RSI_10_SPY"] = RSI_10_SPY
    
    # compute RSI of SPY for 20 days
    up_20_SPY = pd.Series.rolling(up_SPY, window=20, center=False).mean()
    down_20_SPY = pd.Series.rolling(down_SPY.abs(), window=20, center=False).mean()
    RS_20_SPY = up_20_SPY / down_20_SPY
    RSI_20_SPY = 100.0 - (100.0 / (1.0 + RS_20_SPY))
    ans_df["RSI_20_SPY"] = RSI_20_SPY
    
    # add target variable Y (rate of change) to the output data frame ans_df
    y = df_symbol[n_days:].values/df_symbol[:-n_days] - 1
    ans_df["Y"] = y
    
    # add the price and the future price of the symbol to the output data frame ans_df
    ans_df["price"] = df_symbol
    ans_df["future_price"] = np.concatenate((df_symbol[n_days:].values, [np.nan]*n_days))
    
    #split ans_df into train_df and test_df by the training end date train_ed
    train_df = ans_df[:train_ed]
    test_df = ans_df[train_ed+dt.timedelta(days=1):]
    train_df = train_df.dropna() #drop na from the training set
    
    return train_df, test_df

1.2 Regression models¶

In this section, we will illustrate the implementations of regression models we use in this project. The regression models include KNN, Bagging, Decision Tree and Random Forest. The Decision Tree and Random Forest methods use classes provided by sci-kit learn model. They are already imported at the beginning of the notebook. The KNN and Bagging methods are implemented by myself as sci-kit learn style classes. Besides the models, a class called BestLearner that provides methods of evaluating models and selecting best model in the training phase is implemented.

In this project, the features of regression models are 18 technical indicators, and the target value is the rate in percentage the stock will change. Remember that our task of stock price predictor is to predict the stock price, not the rate of change. After we predict the rate of change, the future stock price can by easily computed by multiplying the price at the query date with (1 + predicted rate of change).

The implementations of these models are shown as follows.

1.2.1 K-Nearest- Neighbors Regression Model¶

The class KNNLearner is included in KNN.py. The modules numpy and pandas need to be imported before the class is built.

The class KNNLearner builds a KNN regression model object and provides a method to make prediction on new input instances. The default k is 3, and you can adjust k to any value you want in the class initialization step. The methods in the class is sci-kit learner style. The detailed code is as follows:

In [4]:
class KNNLearner(object):
    """
    The class builds a KNN regression model object and provides a method
        to make prediction on new input points.

    """
    
    def __init__(self, k=3, verbose=False):
        #initialize the k in KNN model.
        self.k = k
        
    def fit(self, dataX, dataY):
        """
        This method stores the training X and Y respectively for the 
            use of the future prediction.

        @param dataX: 2-d array
        @param dataY: Series
        """
        self.X = dataX
        self.Y = dataY
        
        
    def predict(self, points):
        """
        The method takes a 2-d array as input and return a 1-d array
            as the prediction based on the KNN algorithm.
        
        @param points: must be 2d -array, if not reshape it
        @return: 1d-array, predicted values
        """

        #reshape points to 2-d array if points is 1-d array
        if len(points.shape) == 1:
            points = points.reshape(1, -1)

        ans = np.array([])
        for i in range(points.shape[0]):
            xi = points[i]
            dists = np.sqrt(((self.X - xi) ** 2).sum(axis=1)) #find distances
            idxes = dists.argsort()[:self.k] #sort distances and get the first kth
            pred_y = self.Y[idxes].mean() #compute the mean of the k values as the prediction
            ans = np.append(ans, [pred_y])
        return ans

1.2.2 Bagging for KNN model¶

The code of BagLearner class is included in

The BagLearner class builds a bagging ensemble model. The default base regression model in the ensemble is the KNN model that was described in the above. Each base model is fitted on a bootstrapped data set. The default ensemble size 20, and it can be adjusted during the class initialization. The class is also a sci-kit learn style, which provides fit() and predict() methods. The details of the class is shown in below code.

In [5]:
class BagLearner(object):
    """
    The class builds a bagging ensemble model that contains many base regression models.
    The base regression models in the bagging ensemble is KNN model.
    Each model is built based on the data set bootstraped from the training data.
    The default number of KNN models in the bag is 20, and it can be changed 
        during the initialization.
    The class also provides a method to make predictions on new inputs.
    """
    
    def __init__(self, learner=KNNLearner, kwargs={"k":3}, n_learners=20, random_state=817):
        """
        @param leaner: base leaner class, defaulst is the KNN model 
        @param n_leaners: int, number of base leaners in the bag, default is 20

        self.leaners: list, store leaners
        """
        self.random_state = random_state
        self.learners = []
        self.n_learners = n_learners
        
        #initialize the base KNN regression models in bagging ensemble
        for i in range(self.n_learners):
            self.learners.append(learner(**kwargs))
        
    
    def fit(self, dataX, dataY):
        """
        For each leaner in the bag, the function bootstraps
           the training data and fit the model.

        @param dataX: 2d-array
        @param dataY: Series
        """
        n = dataX.shape[0]
        # n is the number of training instances

        #set seed for reproduce result
        np.random.seed(self.random_state)

        for i in range(self.n_learners):
            #bootstrap n indices
            idxes = np.random.choice(n, n)
        
            X = dataX[idxes] #bootstrap training X
            Y = dataY[idxes] #bootstrap training Y
            self.learners[i].fit(X, Y) #train each KNN base model.
    
    def predict(self, points):
        """
        @param points: ndarray
        @return: 1-d array
        """
        ans = self.learners[0].predict(points)
        # ans is a 1-d array

        for i in range(1, self.n_learners):
            ans += self.learners[i].predict(points)
        
        #average the predictions of learners in the bag    
        ans = ans / self.n_learners
        return ans

1.2.3 Best regression model¶

The BestLearner class provides methods that evaluate models of KNN, Bagging, Decision Tree and Random Forest based on the performance of validation data set, and select the best one as the final regression model of the predictor system. It is included in BestLearner.py.

As described before, the target varible of the regression models is the rate of change of the stock in the future. After we obtained the predicted rate of change from a model, the predicted stock price can be easily computed by multipying the stock price of the query date with (1 + predicted rate of change). The metrics to evaluate the performance of the models we use in this project is the mean absolute percentage error (MAPE), which is defined as follows. Suppose the target values of the validation set are $\{y_{1}, y_{2}, ..., y_{n}\}$, and the corresponding predicted target values by a KNN learner are $\{\hat{y_{1}}, \hat{y_{2}},..., \hat{y_{n}}\}$, then the MAPE is $$ \text{MAPE} = \frac{\sum_{i=1}^{n} |y_{i}-\hat{y_{i}}|}{n} $$

The class object of the BestLearner class is initialized by inputing a dataframe of training data obtained from the function process_data(). The input training dataframe contains technical indicators and rate of change as target variable (Y) and stock prices and future actual prices of the stock. In the init() method, the input training data set is firstly divided into two parts: a smaller training set and a validation set. The smaller training set is the first 75% of the input training data set, and the validation data set is the remaining 25% of the input training data set. Then the input training data set, the smaller training data set and the validation data set are normalized respectively.

Then we build regression models based on the smaller training set using KNN, BagLearner, Regression Tree and Random Forest methods, each of which attempts different choices of tuning paramters.

The method bestKNN() firstly builds 18 KNN regression models that uses different integer k ranging from 3 to 20 respectively on the smaller training data set. These 18 KNN regression models are then evaluated by computing MAPE on the validation data set. The best KNN learner is then selected as the one with the minimum MAPE. The method returns k value (optimal_k) of the best KNN learner and its corresponding MAPE value. This method uses the KNNLearner class implemented above.

The method bestBagLearner() firstly builds 9 Bagging models that uses 20, 30, ..., 100 as the size of the ensemble (n_learners) respectively on the normalized smaller training data set. The base model in the Bagging is the KNN learner. The k we use in each KNN learner is the optimal k returned from the bestKNN method. For each of the 9 Bagging models, the MAPE on the validation data set is computed. The best Bagging model is then selected as the one that has the minimum MAPE value. The method returns the size (optimal_n) of the best Bagging model and its corresponding MAPE. This method uses the BagLearner class that has been implemented above.

The method bestTree() firstly builds 6 regreesion tree models that have different complexities. The method uses the DecisionTreeRegressor() method from sci-kit learn module to fit each tree model. The complexity of each tree is controlled by the argument min_samples_split of the DecisionTreeRegressor() method. The values 5, 10, 15, 20, 25 and 30 will be attempted to the argument min_samples_split respectively. All the 6 tree models are built based on the normalized smaller training data set. Then, the MAPEs of theses 6 models on the validation data set are computed. The method selects the tree model that has the minimum MAPE value as the best tree model. The method then returns the min_samples_split of the best tree model (optimal_min_samples_split) and its corresponding MAPE.

The method bestForest() firstly builds 9 Random Forest models which have the size of the ensemble 20, 30, 40,..., 100 respectively. Each random forest model is built using the RandomForestRegressor() function from sci-kit learn module. The size of each random forest is controlled by the argument n_estimators in RandomForestRegressor() function. Each random forest is built based on the smaller training set. Then, the MAPEs of the random forests are computed on the validation set. The method selects the Random Forest that has the minimum MAPE as the best Random Forest among these 9 models. Then the method returns the ensemble size (optimal_n_trees) of the best Random Forest and the corresponding MAPE.

The method get_best_learner() selects the best regression model from the KNN, Bagging, Decision Tree and Random Forest models. First of all, the get_best_learner() method calls bestKNN(), bestBagLearner(), bestTree() and bestForest() methods respectively. Then the MAPEs returned by these 4 methods are compared. The method that has the minimum MAPE will be chosen as the best method. For example, if the MAPE returned by bestForest() has the smallest value, then the best regression method will be the Random Forest method that uses the ensemble size returned by bestForest(). Then we use the best method and its corresponding optimal tuning parameter to fit the final model on the whole training data (the normalized one before dividing into smaller one and validation set). Then best model will be stored as self.best_model for further prediction.

The method fit() is a sci-kit learn style method for predicting the target value of a given instance using the best regression model constructed by the get_best_learner() method.

The detailed code of the clss BestLearner() is given as follows.

In [6]:
class BestLearner(object):
    """
    The class object is initialized by inputing a training dataframe.
    The input dataframe contains stock indicators and rate of change as target variable 
        and stock prices and future actual prices of a specific symbol.
    The training set is divided into a smaller training set and a validation set.
    Several models are built based on the smaller training set.
    The models are KNN, BagLearner, Regression Tree and Random Forest.
    These models are built using different tunning parameters.
    These models are evaluated based on the validation set and the optimal model with 
        the optimal tunning parameters is obtained.
    The model evaluation metrics used is the mean absolute percentage error (mape) on 
        the validation set.
    Using the optimal tunning parameters, the optimal model is built again based on the 
        whole training set (combine small training set and validation set). 
    This final optimal model is used for the future prediction.
    """

    def __init__(self, df_train):
        """
        @param df_train: processed dataframe of a specific symbol
                        It contains stock indicators and 
                        rate of change as target variable and
                        stock prices and future actual prices.
        @initialization:
        self.df_train: processed dataframe, df_train, including xs and y and prices 

        self.mean:          columns means, for normalization
        self.std:           columns std, for normalization
        self.trainX_normed: 2-d array, normalized training x
        self.trainY:        Series, training y 

        self.small_trainX_normed: 2-d array, normalized small training x
        self.small_trainY:        Series, small training y

        self.validationX_normed:     2-d array, normalized validation x
        self.validationPrices:       prices of the symbol in validation set
        self.validationFuturePrices: future actual prices of the symbol in the validation set 
        """
        self.df_train = df_train
        trainX = self.df_train[self.df_train.columns[:-3]].values
        self.mean = trainX.mean(axis = 0)
        self.std = trainX.std(axis = 0)
        self.trainX_normed = (trainX - self.mean) / self.std
        self.trainY = self.df_train["Y"]

        n = trainX.shape[0]
        small_train_size = int(n * 0.75)

        small_trainX = trainX[:small_train_size]
        small_mean = small_trainX.mean(axis = 0)
        small_std = small_trainX.std(axis = 0)
        self.small_trainX_normed = (small_trainX - small_mean) / small_std
        #self.small_trainX is a ndarray

        self.small_trainY = self.trainY[:small_train_size]
        #self.small_trainY is a Series

        validationX = trainX[small_train_size:]
        self.validationX_normed = (validationX - small_mean) / small_std
        #self.validationX is a ndarray

        self.validationPrices = self.df_train["price"][small_train_size:]
        #self.validationPrices is a Series

        self.validationFuturePrices = self.df_train["future_price"][small_train_size:]
        #self.validationFuturePrices is a Series

    def bestKNN(self):
        """
        The method builds several KNN learners with different k based on small training set.
        Then these learners are evaluated based on the validation set.
        The optimal learner with optimal k then is selected. 

        @return: optimal int k, which denotes the optimal k of the optimal KNN learner 
                 that give the best performance on validation set, 
                 and the corresponding mean absolute percentage error (mape)
                
        The performance metrics is the mean absolute percentage error (mape)
        between predicted future prices and actual future prices of validation set.

        The choices of k are integers ranging from 3 to 20.
        """
        optimal_mape = 1
        optimal_k = 3

        for k in range(3, 20):
            knn = KNNLearner(k = k)
            knn.fit(self.small_trainX_normed, self.small_trainY) #fit a KNN model
            predicted_roc = knn.predict(self.validationX_normed) #predict the rate of change
            predicted_prices = self.validationPrices * (1 + predicted_roc) #compute the predicted prices
            mape = np.mean(np.abs(predicted_prices - self.validationFuturePrices) / self.validationFuturePrices)
            #compute MAPE on validation set
            
            #find the minimum MAPE and corresponding optimal k
            if mape < optimal_mape:
                optimal_mape = mape
                optimal_k = k

        return optimal_k, optimal_mape 

    def bestBagLearner(self):
        """
        The method builds several BagLearner models based on small training set. 
        The base model in the BagLearner is the KNN learner.
        The k in KNN learner is obtained by the method self.bestKNN()
        These BagLearner models have different n_learners parameter, which denotes number
        of base learners in the bag. 
        The optimal model with the optimal n_learners will be obtained based on validation set.

        @return: optimal integer n_learners, which denotes the number of learners in the bag

        The choices of n_learners are 20, 30, 40, ..., 100
        """
        k = self.bestKNN()[0] # compute the optimal k by bestKNN() method
        #k will be used for constructing base model in the bagging ensemble
        
        optimal_n = 20
        optimal_mape = 1
        
        #try different bagging models with different ensemble size
        for n_learners  in range(20, 101, 10):
            bag = BagLearner(learner=KNNLearner, kwargs={"k":k}, n_learners=n_learners) #bagging model
            bag.fit(self.small_trainX_normed, self.small_trainY)
            predicted_roc = bag.predict(self.validationX_normed) #predict rate of change on validation set
            predicted_prices = self.validationPrices * (1 + predicted_roc)#compute predicted prices on validation set
            
            #compute MAPE on validation set
            mape = np.mean(np.abs(predicted_prices - self.validationFuturePrices) / self.validationFuturePrices)
            
            #update the minimum MAPE and corresponding optimal ensemble size
            if mape < optimal_mape:
                optimal_mape = mape
                optimal_n = n_learners

        return optimal_n, optimal_mape

    def bestTree(self):
        """
        The method builds a set of regression tree models with different tunning paramters 
            based on the small training set.
        The tunning parameter used is the min_samples_split, which is a parameter for controling 
            the complexity of the tree.
        The values of min_samples_split are: 5, 10, 15, 20, 25, 30.
        The optimal tree with the optimal min_samples_split is obtained based on validation set.
        
        @return: optimal min_samples_split, the mape on validation set
        """
        optimal_min_samples_split = 5
        optimal_mape = 1

        for min_samples_split in range(5, 31, 5):
            tree = DecisionTreeRegressor(min_samples_split=min_samples_split, random_state=817) #Decision Tree
            tree.fit(self.small_trainX_normed, self.small_trainY)
            predicted_roc = tree.predict(self.validationX_normed) #predict rate of change on validation set
            predicted_prices = self.validationPrices * (1 + predicted_roc) #compute predicted price on validation set
            
            #compute MAPE on validation set
            mape = np.mean(np.abs(predicted_prices - self.validationFuturePrices) / self.validationFuturePrices)
            if mape < optimal_mape:
                optimal_mape = mape
                optimal_min_samples_split = min_samples_split

        return optimal_min_samples_split, optimal_mape

    def bestForest(self):
        """
        The method builds several random forest regression models with different n_estimators values 
            based on small training set.
        The tunning parameter n_estimators denotes the number of trees in the forest.
        These forest models then are evaluated based on the validation set.
        The optimal n_estimators is obtained.

        @return: optimal n_estimators, corresponding mape on validation set
        """
        optimal_mape = 1
        optimal_n_trees = 20

        for n_trees in range(20, 101, 10):
            forest = RandomForestRegressor(n_estimators=n_trees, random_state=817) #Random Forest
            forest.fit(self.small_trainX_normed, self.small_trainY)
            predicted_roc = forest.predict(self.validationX_normed)#predict rate of change on validation set
            predicted_prices = self.validationPrices * (1 + predicted_roc)#compute predicted price on validation set
            
            #compute MAPE on validation set
            mape = np.mean(np.abs(predicted_prices - self.validationFuturePrices) / self.validationFuturePrices)
            if mape < optimal_mape:
                optimal_mape = mape
                optimal_n_trees = n_trees

        return optimal_n_trees, optimal_mape


    def get_best_learner(self):
        """
        The method compares optimal KNN, BagLearner, tree and random forest based on their mapes
            and the best model among these 4 models is selected as the final best model.
        The final best model is fit again using the whole training set, not just the small training set.
        The best model is stored in self.best_model. 
        Also, the values of the tunning parameters in the best model are stored in self.best
        """
        
        #Fit different models, return their minimum MAPEs and corresponding optimal tunning parameters
        k, mape_knn = self.bestKNN()

        n, mape_bag = self.bestBagLearner()

        mss, mape_tree = self.bestTree()

        n_trees, mape_forest = self.bestForest()
        
        self.models_info = (
            {"method":"KNN", "k": k, "mape_knn":mape_knn},
            {"method":"Bagging", "n_bag":n, "mape_bag": mape_bag},
            {"method":"Tree", "min_sample_split": mss, "mape_tree":mape_tree},
            {"method":"RF", "n_trees": n_trees, "mape_forest": mape_forest}
        )

        best = "knn"
        best_mape = mape_knn
        
        #Compare the performance (MAPE) of these models, and select the best one
        if mape_bag < best_mape:
            best = "bag"
            best_mape = mape_bag

        if mape_tree < best_mape:
            best = "tree"
            best_mape = mape_tree

        if mape_forest < best_mape:
            best = "forest"
            best_mape = mape_forest
        
        #Initialize the best model
        if best == "knn":
            self.best_model = KNNLearner(k = k)
            self.best = {"model":best, "k":k, "mape on validation": best_mape}


        elif best == "bag":
            self.best_model = BagLearner(learner=KNNLearner, kwargs={"k":k})
            self.best = {"model":best, "n_learners":n, "k":k, "mape on validation": best_mape}

        elif best == "tree":
            self.best_model = DecisionTreeRegressor(min_samples_split=mss, random_state=817)
            self.best = {"model":best, "min_samples_split":mss, "mape on validation": best_mape}

        else:
            self.best_model = RandomForestRegressor(n_estimators=n_trees, random_state=817)
            self.best = {"model":best, "n_trees":n_trees, "mape on validation": best_mape}
        
        #fit the best model
        self.best_model.fit(self.trainX_normed, self.trainY)


    def predict(self, points):
        """
        @param points: must be 2-d array, if 1-d array, then reshape it to 2-d array
        @return: 1-d array

        The method takes a 2-d array of technical indicator values as input.
        The self.best_model is used to make the prediction of the future price based on the input.
        """
        
        # points needs to be normalized first before making the prediction
        points_normed = (points - self.mean) / self.std
        
        return self.best_model.predict(points_normed)

1.3 Stock Price Predictor¶

So far, we have implemented the functions for obtaining and pre-processing stock data, and classes for fitting regression models and selecting the best one among them. In this section, we will combine these functions and classes together by implementing the StockIndicator class. The StockIndicator class is the core of the User Interface of Stock Price Predictor. It is included in StockIndicator.py file.

The StockIndicator class is initialized by storing the inputs: the stock symbols (self.symbols), the training start date (self.train_sd), the training end date (self.train_ed) and the prediction interval (self.n_days).

The processing_data() method calls the get_data() and the process_data() functions from section 1.1 to process the stock data for fitting regression models. self.processed_train is a dictionary where the key is a symbol and the corresponding value is the training data set of that symbol. self.processed_test is a dictionary where the key is a stock symbol and the corresponding value is the testing data set of that symbol ranging from the date self.train_ed to present.

The learn_from_data() method constructs objects of BestLearner class which build the best regression model based on the training data for each of the stock symbols. The self.best_learners is a dictionary that stores the best regression models for each of the symbols. The key of the self.best_learners dictionary is a stock symbol and the corresponding value is a BestLearner object that consists of the best regression model of the stock.

The predict() method predicts the Adjusted Close prices of the stocks. The input of the method is the query date (current_date). The query date (current_date) needs to be a trading day, if not, then the prediction will be 0. The prediction is the stock price of the day that is self.n_days trading days after the current_date.

The StockIndicator class implementation is as follows.

In [7]:
class StockIndicator(object):

    def __init__(self, symbols, train_sd, train_ed, n_days):
        """
        @param symbols: list of stock names
        @param train_sd: start date, datetime object
        @param train_ed: end date 
        @param n_days: int, days interval for prediction 
        """
        self.symbols = symbols
        self.train_sd = train_sd
        self.train_ed = train_ed
        self.n_days = n_days

    def processing_data(self):
        """
        the function generates self.all_prices, self.processed_train, self.processed_test
        self.all_prices: dataframe, symbols+SPY prices, from train_sd to present
        self.processed_train: dict for processed training data of different symbols
        self.processed_test: dict for processed data starting from training end date to present
        processed data: data frame consisting of many technical indicators
        """


        self.all_prices = get_data(self.symbols, self.train_sd) 
        #dataframe, symbols+SPY prices, from train_sd to present
        
        self.dates = self.all_prices.index

        self.processed_train = {} #dict for processed training data
        self.processed_test = {} #dict for processed data from train_ed to present

        for symbol in self.symbols:
            df_train, df_test = process_data(self.all_prices, symbol, self.train_ed, self.n_days)
            #process_data() from DataGetter.py separates train and test data for each symbol

            #store each symbol's processed train and test data to dicts
            self.processed_train[symbol] = df_train
            self.processed_test[symbol] = df_test

    def learn_from_data(self):
        """
        The function generates the dict self.best_learners, which contains best 
        learners for each of the symbols.
        """
        self.best_learners = {}
        for symbol in self.symbols:
            df_train = self.processed_train[symbol]

            best_learner = BestLearner(df_train)
            best_learner.get_best_learner()
            self.best_learners[symbol] = best_learner 

    def predict(self, current_date):
        """
        The function computes technical indicators of current_date, and 
        predict stock prices of symbols self.n_days after current_date.

        @param current_date: datetime object, the query date
        @return: predicted prices at the date that self.n_days after current_date
        """
        if current_date not in self.dates:
            return 0

        predictions = {}

        for symbol in self.symbols:
            if current_date <= self.train_ed:
                test_df = self.processed_train[symbol]
            else:
                test_df = self.processed_test[symbol]
            testX = test_df[test_df.columns[:-3]].ix[current_date].values
            #testX is a 1-d array, so we need to reshape it to 2-d array
            testX = testX.reshape(1, -1)

            predY = self.best_learners[symbol].predict(testX)[0] # rate of change
            #predY is a scalar, extracted from a one-element array
            
            #predicted price is then computed based on the price  of query date and the predicted rate of change
            pred_price = self.all_prices[symbol][current_date] * (1 + predY)
            predictions[symbol] = pred_price
            
        return predictions

1.4 User Interface of Stock Predictor¶

The class StockIndicator is used to build a User Interface of Stock Predictor. The code of the interface is included in the main function of StockIndicator.py. This interface can be run in the terminal. I have already test this user interface under the system Ubuntu 14.04. The python version is 2.7x. Before you run the interface, you need to make sure that you have already installed all the modules imported at the beginning of this notebook.

In order to run the interface in the terminal, you need to store the files DataGetter.py, KNN.py, BagLearner.py, BestLearner.py and StockIndicator.py under the same folder. Then you open a terminal and go to the path of the folder that contains these file. You type: python StockIndicator.py, you will enter the interface. The interface will ask you to input some information such as stock symbols, prediction interval etc. step by step. Then the interface will run the code we illustrated in the above sections to fit regression models and make predictions for you.

The interface can also be run in this notebook. The code of the main function in StockIndicator.py is shown below. We will present the interface by running it in this notebook. We will use the same example shown in section 1.3, which predicts the Adjusted Close price of stocks Google and IBM. The training data is from 01/01/2011 to 12/31/2014. And the prediction interval is 5 trading days. After the model is finalized, we will use the interface to predict the stock prices of Google and IBM on the day that 5 trading days after 01/06/2015 (query date).

When we execute the code below, the first thing the interface want you to input is the stock symbols. What we need to input is: "GOOG IBM". Please don't forget the quotes ("") when input. Then the interface will ask you to input the training start date, where you need to input "2011-01-01". Then the interface will ask you to input the training end date, where you need to input "2014-12-31". You need to input the dates exactly the same as showed to make sure the interface work, and don't forget the quotes. Then you will need to input the prediction interval, which in this example is 5 (do not need quotes). Then, the interface will fit the regression models. This process will take a couple of minutes. After the model fitting is finished, the interface will ask you to input the current date. In this example, you should input "2015-01-06". Then the predictions will be shown. After the predictions are shown, the interface will ask you if you want to continue make other predictions or not. In this case, we will input "n" as a no.

After running the interface, you will find that the predictions by the interface is the same as the predictions in the example shown in section 1.3. You can also use this interface to make predictions of other stocks. And the date range, the prediction interval can also be adjusted as you wish. When you run this interface in the terminal using the same example, you will get the same result.

2. case studies based on the stock predictor¶

In this section, we implement a class TradeStock that provides methods to conduct case studies. There will be three case studies in this project. They are:

  • Google: training date range: 01/01/2011-12/31/2014, testing date range: 01/01/2015-12/31/2015
  • Apple: training date range: 01/01/2003-12/31/2007, testing date range: 01/01/2008-12/31/2008
  • IBM: training date range: 01/01/2010-12/31/2013, testing date range: 01/01/2014-12/31/2014

In each case study, we will attempt three different prediction intervals: 5, 10 and 20 trading days. For each prediction interval, we build a stock price predictor and compute the MAPE of the final model of the predictor on the validation set. The MAPEs of different prediction intervals are compared, and the prediction interval corresponds to minimum MAPE will be used to construct the trading strategy. When the prediction interval is decided, we will use the corresponding predictor to make predictions on testing set. The performance of the predictor on testing set is evaluated by MAPE. Besides, we will develop a trading strategy based on the prediction of future stock price given by the stock price predictor. Then we will use the trading strategy to trade the stock during the testing date range. The starting investment value will be 100000 US dollars. The portfolio values based on the trading strategy will be computed. To evaluate the trading strategy, the cummulative return and Sharpe ratio will be used as metrics. Also, the stock price over the testing date range will be used as the benchmark to compare with the portfolio values. All these works are done by methods in the TradeStock class.

First of all, the object of TradeStock class is initialized by inputing symbol, train_sd, train_ed, test_sd, test_ed, n_days. symbol is the name of a stock that will be investigate in the study. train_sd and train_ed denote the training start date and the training end date respectively. test_sd and test_ed denote the testing start date and the testing end date respectively. The test_sd should be after the train_ed. n_days denotes the prediction interval in terms of number of days. In the init method, we firstly extract the stock price using get_data() function described in section 1. Then, we divide the stock price data into training data set and the testing data set according to the training date range (train_sd and train_ed) and the testing date range (test_sd and test_ed). We then construct an object of BestLearner class and train our final regression model on the training data set for the given prediction interval. This regression model is to predict the rate of change of the future stock price.

The core content of method create_oreders() is the trading strategy we use in this project. The method create_orders() generates orders of the stock during the testing date range using the trading strategy built based on the prediction of future stock price. The argument price_pred_df is a dataframe that each row index is a date in the testing date range. In the price_pred_df, for each day (row), we have the stock price at that day and the predicted stock price that n_days trading days after that day. The predicted stock prices are computed using the final regression model, and this procedure is done in get_orders() method, which uses create_orders() method as a helper method. In the create_orders() method, each orders is developed as either "BUY" or "SELL" of 100 shares. The trading strategy that develops orders is as follows. For each day (let's call it today) during the testing date range, we extract the stock price and the predicted future stock price from the price_pred_df, and compare them.

  1. According to the comparison, if the stock price will rise in the future, we "BUY" 100 shares of the stock at today. We then hold our position to the due_day which is n_days (n trading days) after today. If the price at due_day is greater than or equal to the predicted price at today, then we "SELL" 100 shares of the stock to finish this round of trade. Otherwise, we continue holding these 100 shares to a day that the price of the day is greater than or equal to the predicted price of today, and "SELL" 100 shares to finish this round of trade. Besides, we also set a stop loss strategy here after we "BUY" 100 shares at today. During the days after today, if this round of trade is not finished, and if the price of a day is less than 90% of the price of today, we stop loss by "SELL" 100 shares and finish this round of trade.

  2. According to the comparison, if the stock price will drop in the future, we short ("SELL") 100 shares of the stock at today. We then hold our short position to the due_day which is n_days (n trading days) after today. If the price at due_day is less than or equal to the predicted price at today, then we "BUY" 100 shares of the stock to finish this round of trade. Otherwise, we continue holding the position of short 100 shares to a day that the price of the day is less than or equal to the predicted price of today, and "SELL" 100 shares to finish this round of trade. Besides, we also set a stop loss strategy here after we short 100 shares at today. During the days after today, if this round of trade is not finished, and if the price of a day is more than 110% of the price of today, we stop loss by "BUY" 100 shares and finish this round of trade.

Based on the strategy described above, the orders of "BUY" and "SELL" are generated and saved as a dataframe (orders_df). The index of the orders_df are the dates we make orders. At each row, we have three columns that indicates the name of the stock, the order we make and the number of the shares respectively. The orders_df is returned by create_orders().

The get_orders() method generates a dataframe that contains the orders of the input stock. Firstly, we predict the future stock prices using predict() method of BestLearner object. Then, we generate the orders dataframe using the helper method created_orders().

The compute_values() method computes the stock value and the cash value we have at each day during the testing date range. This method will be used as a helper method in get_portvals() method. The method has 3 input arguments: orders_df, prices_df and start_val. The orders_df is a dataframe that consists of orders of the stock during the testing date range. It is obtained by the get_orders() method. The argument prices_df is a dataframe consisting of the stock prices during the testing date range. The argument start_val is an integer that indicates the total value in US dollars you have at the beginning of the testing start date. The default start_val is 100000 USD. The method returns a dataframe called values_df. The index of the values_df are the dates in testing date range. For each day (row) in the dataframe, one column indicates the value of the stock we hold at that day, and the other column indicates the value of cash we have at that day.

The get_portvals() method computes the portfolio value of days during the tesitng date range. Firstly, we compute the order_df by calling the get_orders() method. Then, we compute the values_df by calling compute_values() method. Finally, the portfolio values dataframe portvals is obtained by sum up the columns of values_df. The returned dataframe portvals contains only one column: "Portfolio Value". The index of the portvals are the dates in testing date range. At each row (day), the value indicates the portfolio value at that day, i.e., it is the sum of the value of stock we hold and the value of cash we have at that day.

The compute_daily_returns() method takes the portfolio values during testing date range as input argument, and compute the daily returns. The daily return of the first day is set to be 0. The argument portvals is a pandas Series that contains portfolio values. The returned dataframe has one column, and each row value is a daily return.

The normalize_data() method normalizes the portfolio values. The input argument portvals is a pandas Series that contains portfolio values during testing date range. The returned value is a Series consisting of normalized portfolio values.

The create_results() method generates the result of the case study. First of all, the MAPE between predicted stock price and actual stock price at the testing range is computed and printed. Secondly, the portfolio values of the input stock during the test date range are obtained by calling the get_portvals() method. Then, we compute the cumulative return, the daily returns, the mean and std of daily returns, and Sharpe ratio of the portfolio values. To evaluate the performance of our trading strategy built based on prediction of stock price by regression model, we also compute the cumulative return, the daily returns, the mean and std of daily returns, and Sharpe ratio of the stock prices during the tesint date range, and comapre them with the resutls of the portfolios. These results will be printed at the screen when executing the method. Besides, two plots will be made. The first plot is shows the comparison between the predicted stock price and the actual stock price during the testing date range. Also, we normalize the portfolio values and the stock prices and plot them within one graph for comparison. The graph will be saved in the current working directory.
