class TradeStock(object):
    """
    This class performs the case study of trading stocks.
    To initialize an object of the class, the stock symbol, traning start date, training end date,
        testing start date, testing end date and prediction interval are input at the beginning.
    Regression models are fitted on stock price data of training date range, and the best regression model
        is selected for further prediction.
    The regression model is used to predict the rate of change of the future stock price, and the prediction of 
        future stock price is computed based on the predicted rate of change.
    A trading strategy is made based on the prediction of future price in create_order() method.
    We use the trading strategy to make orders during the testing date range.
    Then, we compute Cumulative Return, Daily Returns and Sharpe Ratios of portfolio values during the testing 
        date range to evaluate our strategy.
    The results generated by the stock price are used as benchmark to compare with our portfolio results.
    """

    def __init__(self, symbol, train_sd, train_ed, test_sd, test_ed, n_days):
        """
        @param symbol: a string, stock name
        @param train_sd: training start date, datetime object
        @param train_ed: training end date
        @param test_sd: testing start date
        @param test_ed: testing end date
        @param n_days: int, number of days, prediction interval 
        """

        df_allprices = get_data([symbol], train_sd) #call get_data() to exact stock data
        
        self.prices_to_plot = df_allprices[[symbol]][train_sd:test_ed] #stock prices for visualization in the report
        
        #call process_data() to pre-process data, and get training and testing data sets.
        self.df_train, df_test = process_data(df_allprices, symbol, train_ed, n_days) 
        self.df_test = df_test[:test_ed]
        
        #prices of the stock ranging from the test start date to the test end date
        self.prices_df = df_allprices[[symbol]][test_sd:test_ed]

        self.symbol = symbol
        self.n_days = n_days
        
        #construct a BestLearner object and train the best regression model
        self.best_learner = BestLearner(self.df_train)
        self.best_learner.get_best_learner()

    def create_orders(self, price_pred_df, symbol, n_days):
        """
        This method generates a dataframe that contains orders of a given stock.
        The orders are either "BUY" or "SELL", each order is 100 shares.
        The orders are generated by the trading strategy based on the stock predictions.
        This method is a helper function that will be used in the method get_orders().
        
        @param price_pred_df: dataframe, contains stock prices and predicted future prices as columns
        @symbol: string, the name of the stock
        @n_days: int, prediction interval in number of days
        
        @return: a dataframe, columns are "Symbol", "Order", "Shares"
                     "Symbol": contains the stock name
                     "Order": either "BUY" or "SELL"
                     "Shares": times of 100
                     the index of the returned data frame are dates
        """
        
        #initialize the returned dataframe
        orders_df = pd.DataFrame(columns = ["Symbol", "Order", "Shares"])
        
        dates = price_pred_df.index
    
        for i in range(len(dates) - n_days):
            today = dates[i] #today, the day that make "BUY" or "SELL" decision based on the prediction of n_days later
            days_in_between = dates[i+1:i+n_days-1] #days between today and n_days later
            due_day = dates[i+n_days] #due_day: the day that n_days after today
            days_after_due_day = dates[i+n_days:] #days after the due_day
            finish_trade = False #indicator if a pair of "BUY" and "SELL" order is finished
        
            if price_pred_df.ix[today]["price"] < price_pred_df.ix[today]["predicted future price"]:
            #if today's price is less than the predicted future price of n_days later:
                
                #Then, we make a "BUY" order of 100 shares
                temp = pd.DataFrame(columns = ["Symbol", "Order", "Shares"])
                temp.ix[today] = [symbol, "BUY", 100]
                orders_df = orders_df.append(temp)
                
                #Set a stop loss strategy:
                #If at a day between today and n_days later, the price drops over 10% compared to today's price,
                #Then, we stop loss by "SELL" 100 shares of the stock
                for day in days_in_between:
                    if not finish_trade and price_pred_df.ix[day]["price"] < price_pred_df.ix[today]["price"]*0.9:
                        temp = pd.DataFrame(columns = ["Symbol", "Order", "Shares"])
                        temp.ix[day] = [symbol, "SELL", 100]
                        orders_df = orders_df.append(temp)
                        finish_trade = True
                    
                #If we didn't stop loss during days_in_between:
                if not finish_trade:       
                    
                    #If the price at due_day (n_days after today) is greater or equal to the predicted price of due_day:
                    #Then we "SELL" 100 shares of the stock
                    if price_pred_df.ix[due_day]["price"] >= price_pred_df.ix[today]["predicted future price"]:
                        temp = pd.DataFrame(columns = ["Symbol", "Order", "Shares"])
                        temp.ix[due_day] = [symbol, "SELL", 100]
                        orders_df = orders_df.append(temp)
                        
                    #else (the price at due_day is less than the predicted price of due_day):
                    #Then we will not "SELL" 100 shares of the stock at due_day, we continue holding the shares and wait...
                    #Hold shares until the price of the stock is grater or equal to the predicted price of due_day, we "SELL" 100 shares.
                    #But during the days of holding, if the price drops more than 10% compare to the price of today, we stop loss by "SELL" 100 shares
                    else:
                        
                        #Hold the stock after due_day
                        for day in days_after_due_day:
                            
                            #If the price of a day after due_day is greater or equal to the predicted price of due_day:
                            #Then we "SELL" 100 shares
                            if not finish_trade and price_pred_df.ix[day]["price"] >= price_pred_df.ix[today]["predicted future price"]:
                                temp = pd.DataFrame(columns = ["Symbol", "Order", "Shares"])
                                temp.ix[day] = [symbol, "SELL", 100]
                                orders_df = orders_df.append(temp)
                                finish_trade = True
                                
                            #If the price of a day after due_day drops more than 10% compared to the price of today,
                            #Then we stop loss by "SELL" 100 shares
                            elif not finish_trade and price_pred_df.ix[day]["price"] < price_pred_df.ix[today]["price"]*0.9:
                                temp = pd.DataFrame(columns = ["Symbol", "Order", "Shares"])
                                temp.ix[day] = [symbol, "SELL", 100]
                                orders_df = orders_df.append(temp)
                                finish_trade = True


            # If the price of today is less the predicted future price of due_day (n_days later),
            #Then, we short 100 shares by "SELL" orders.
            else:
                temp = pd.DataFrame(columns = ["Symbol", "Order", "Shares"])
                temp.ix[today] = [symbol, "SELL", 100]
                orders_df = orders_df.append(temp)
            
                # During the days between today and the due_day, if price increased more than 10% compared to today's price,
                # Then we stop loss by "BUY" 100 shares
                for day in days_in_between:
                    if not finish_trade and price_pred_df.ix[day]["price"] > price_pred_df.ix[today]["price"]*1.1:
                        temp = pd.DataFrame(columns = ["Symbol", "Order", "Shares"])
                        temp.ix[day] = [symbol, "BUY", 100]
                        orders_df = orders_df.append(temp)
                        finish_trade = True
                
                #If we didn't stop loss before due_day:
                if not finish_trade:
                    
                    #If the price on due_day is less than or equal to the predicted price:
                    #Then, we "BUY" 100 shares back.
                    if price_pred_df.ix[due_day]["price"] <= price_pred_df.ix[today]["predicted future price"]:
                        temp = pd.DataFrame(columns = ["Symbol", "Order", "Shares"])
                        temp.ix[due_day] = [symbol, "BUY", 100]
                        orders_df = orders_df.append(temp)
                        
                    #else (the price on due_day is greater than the predicted price):
                    #Then, we continue holding the short position, and wait..
                    else:
                        for day in days_after_due_day:
                            
                            #if at a day after due_day, the price is less than or equal to the predicted price of due_day:
                            #Then we "BUY" 100 shares back.
                            if not finish_trade and price_pred_df.ix[day]["price"] <= price_pred_df.ix[today]["predicted future price"]:
                                temp = pd.DataFrame(columns = ["Symbol", "Order", "Shares"])
                                temp.ix[day] = [symbol, "BUY", 100]
                                orders_df = orders_df.append(temp)
                                finish_trade = True
                                
                            #if at a day after due_day, the price is 10% more than the price of today:
                            #Then we stop loss by "BUY" 100 shares back.
                            elif not finish_trade and price_pred_df.ix[day]["price"] > price_pred_df.ix[today]["price"]*1.1:
                                temp = pd.DataFrame(columns = ["Symbol", "Order", "Shares"])
                                temp.ix[day] = [symbol, "BUY", 100]
                                orders_df = orders_df.append(temp)
                                finish_trade = True
    
        return orders_df
  

    def get_orders(self):
        """
        This method generates a dataframe that contains the orders of the input stock.
        Firstly, we predict the future stock prices using predict() method of BestLearner object
        Then, we generate the orders data frame using the helper method created_orders()
        
        @return: orders_df, a data frame that has 3 columns "Symbol", "Order" and "Shares"
                        "Symbol": stock name
                        "Order": either "BUY" or "SELL"
                        "Shares": 100
                        index: dates that operate
        """
        
        #extract the features of test data set
        testX = self.df_test[self.df_test.columns[:-3]].values
        
        pred_roc = self.best_learner.predict(testX) #predict the rate of change in the future on test data set
        pred_future_prices = self.df_test["price"] * (1+pred_roc) #compute the predicted future price based on future roc
        pred_future_prices.name = "predicted future price"
        price_pred_df = pd.concat([self.df_test["price"], pred_future_prices], axis=1) 
        #combine price and future predicted price togeter as the input argument of create_orders() method
        
        self.price_pred_df = price_pred_df #for visualization in the report
        
        #call create_orders() method to generate the orders dataframe
        orders_df = self.create_orders(price_pred_df, self.symbol, self.n_days)

        return orders_df


    def compute_values(self, orders_df, prices_df, start_val=100000):
        """
        This method computes the stock value and the cash value we have at each day of testing days.
        This method will be used as a helper method in get_portvals() method.
        
        @param orders_df: dataframe, orders of the stock starting from testing start date to testing end date
        @param prices_df: dataframe, stock prices of the stock from testing start date to testing end date
        @param start_val: int, default 100000, the total value in US dollars you have at the beginning of the testing start date
        
        @return values_df: dataframe consisting of 2 columns which are stock name, and "CASH"
                           For a row in values_df:
                               stock name: value of stock we hold at the date that the row index indicates
                               "CASH": value of cash we have at the date that the row index indicates
        """
        
        #sort the orders_df by date
        orders_df = orders_df.sort_index()
        
        #add a column "CASH" that have values 1s.
        #Then prices_df has 2 columns: stock name, and "CASH"
        prices_df["CASH"] = 1
        
        #initialize the trades_df dataframe by copying the prices_df
        #trades_df has two columns: stock name and "CASH"
        #index of trades_df are the dates from testing start date to testing end date
        #the value of the stock name column at a given row is the change of shares of the stock at the date that the row index indicates
        #the value of "CASH" is at a given row is the change of cash values at the date that the index indicates
        trades_df = prices_df.copy()
        
        #for every trading day from testing start date to testing end date:
        for date in trades_df.index:
            trades_df.ix[date] = 0 # firstly, set the values of both columns at current date to be 0
            
            #if we make an order at the current date:
            if date in orders_df.index:
                orders_today = orders_df.ix[date] #extract the order info of current date
                
                if isinstance(orders_today, pd.DataFrame): #if the number of orders of today > 1
                    
                    #then extract info of every order and update the trades_df
                    for i in range(orders_today.shape[0]):
                        symbol = orders_today.ix[i]["Symbol"]
                        order = orders_today.ix[i]["Order"]
                        shares = orders_today.ix[i]["Shares"]
                        price = prices_df.ix[date][symbol]
                        if order == "BUY":
                            trades_df.ix[date,symbol] += shares 
                            trades_df.ix[date,"CASH"] -= shares*price
                        else:
                            trades_df.ix[date,symbol] -= shares
                            trades_df.ix[date,"CASH"] += shares*price
                else: #the number of orders of today is 1
                    
                    #extract the order information
                    symbol = orders_today["Symbol"]
                    order = orders_today["Order"]
                    shares = orders_today["Shares"]
                    price = prices_df.ix[date][symbol]
                    
                    #update the trades_df
                    if order == "BUY":
                        trades_df.ix[date,symbol] += shares
                        trades_df.ix[date,"CASH"] -= shares*price
                    else:
                        trades_df.ix[date,symbol] -= shares
                        trades_df.ix[date,"CASH"] += shares*price
        
        #initialize the holdings_df as the copy of trades_df
        holdings_df = trades_df.copy()
        
        # set the value of first row of "CASH" column to be the start_val
        holdings_df.ix[0,"CASH"] += start_val
        
        #For each column of holdings_df, we perform cumulative summation
        #Then, for column of stock name, the value at a row indicates the number of shares we hold at the date the row index indicates
        #And for column of "CASH", the value at a row indicates the total cash values we have at the date the row index indicates
        holdings_df = holdings_df.cumsum(axis = 0)
        
        #multiply holdings_df by prices_df element-wisely
        #Then for column of stock name, the value at a row indicates the value of the stock we are holding at the date the row index indicates
        #And for column of "CASH", the value at a row indicates the total cash values we have at the date the row index indicates
        values_df = holdings_df * prices_df

        return values_df

    def get_portvals(self):
        """
        This method computes the portfolio value of each days from the testing start date to testing end date.
        Firstly, the order_df is obtained by calling get_orders() method.
        Then, the values_df is obtained by calling compute_values() method
        Finally, the portfolio values data frame portvals is obtained by sum up the columns of values_df.
        
        @return portvals: dataframe contains one column "Portfolio Value".
                              At each row of the dataframe, the value indicates the portfolio value at the date that the index of the row indicates
                              The portfolio value is the sum of the value of stock we hold and the value of cash we have.
        """
        orders_df = self.get_orders() #get orders_df by calling get_orders() method
        values_df = self.compute_values(orders_df, self.prices_df) #get values_df by calling compute_values() method
        portvals = values_df.sum(axis=1).to_frame(name = "Portfolio Value") #sum 2 columns of values_df to get portvals dataframe
        
        return portvals 

    def compute_daily_returns(self, portvals):
        """
        The method takes the portfolio values as input and compute the daily returns.
        The date range is from testing start date to testing end date
        The daily return of the first day is set to be 0.
        
        @param portvals: Series, contains portfolio values
        
        @return ans_df: dataframe, one column, each row value is daily return
        """
        ans_df = portvals.copy()
        ans_df[1:] = portvals[1:]/portvals[:-1].values - 1
        ans_df.ix[0] = 0
        
        return ans_df

    def normalize_data(self, portvals):
        """
        This method normalize the portfolio values.
        
        @param portvals: Series, contains portfolio values from testing start date to testing end date
        
        @return: a Series consisting of normalized portfolio values
        """
        
        return portvals / portvals[0]


    def create_results(self):
        """
        This method generates the trading results of portfolio values on testing data set.
        The results include: 1. Cumulative Return
                             2. mean of Daily Returns
                             3. standard deviation of Daily Return
                             4. Sharpe Ratio 
        The date range of the testing data set is from testing start date (test_sd) to testing end date (test_ed)
        The prices of the input stock will be used as the benchmark to compare with the portfolio values.
        The results will be shown in the screen when execute this method.
        The plot will be made and saved at current directory when execute this method
        """
        
        #Compute the results based on portfolio values from test_sd to test_ed
        portvals = self.get_portvals()  #obtain portfolio values
        portvals = portvals[portvals.columns[0]]  #transform portvals from a dataframe to Series
        cum_ret = portvals[-1]/portvals[0] - 1  #compute cumulative return of portfolio values
        daily_rets = self.compute_daily_returns(portvals)  #compute daily returns
        daily_rets = daily_rets[1:]  #delete the daily return of the first day
        avg_daily_ret = daily_rets.mean()  #find the mean of daily returns
        std_daily_ret = daily_rets.std()  #find the standard deviation of daily returns 
        sharpe_ratio = np.sqrt(252) * avg_daily_ret / std_daily_ret  #compute sharpe ratio of the portfolio values
        
        #Compute the results based on stock prices from test_sd to test_ed
        symbol_prices = self.prices_df[self.symbol] #extract stock prices as a Series 
        cum_ret_symbol = symbol_prices[-1] / symbol_prices[0] - 1  #compute cumulative return of stock prices
        daily_rets_symbol = self.compute_daily_returns(symbol_prices)  #compute daily returns of stock prices
        daily_rets_symbol = daily_rets_symbol[1:]   #delete the daily return of the first day
        avg_daily_ret_symbol = daily_rets_symbol.mean()  #find the mean of daily returns
        std_daily_ret_symbol = daily_rets_symbol.std()   #find the standard deviation of daily returns 
        sharpe_ratio_symbol = np.sqrt(252) * avg_daily_ret_symbol / std_daily_ret_symbol  #compute sharpe ratio of the stock prices
        
        #normalize portfolio values and stock prices respectively for plotting use
        portvals_norm = self.normalize_data(portvals)
        symbol_norm = self.normalize_data(symbol_prices)
        
        
        #make plot to compare predicted price with actual price during testing date range
        actual_price = self.price_pred_df["price"]
        predict_price = self.price_pred_df["predicted future price"][:-self.n_days]
        predict_price.index = self.price_pred_df.index[self.n_days:]
        fig, ax = plt.subplots( nrows=1, ncols=1 )
        fig.set_size_inches(15, 8)
        actual_price.plot(ax = ax, title = "Actual Price vs Predicted Price", label="Actual Price", color="green")
        predict_price.plot(ax = ax, label="Predicted Price", color="blue")
        ax.set_xlabel("Date")
        ax.set_ylabel("Adjusted Close Price (USD)")
        plt.legend(loc="best")
        fig.savefig("{}.png".format(self.symbol+"_pred_actual"), bbox_inches="tight")
        
        #MAPE on testing set
        mape_test = np.mean(np.abs(actual_price[self.n_days:]-predict_price)/actual_price[self.n_days:])
        
        
        #make plot to compare normalized portfolio values and normalized stock prices during testing date range
        fig, ax = plt.subplots( nrows=1, ncols=1 )
        fig.set_size_inches(15, 8)
        symbol_norm.plot(ax = ax, title = "Normalized Daily Portfolio Value VS Normalized Stock Price", label="Stock Price of "+self.symbol, color="green")
        portvals_norm.plot(ax = ax, label="Portfolio Values", color="blue")
        ax.set_xlabel("Date")
        ax.set_ylabel("Normalized Price")
        plt.legend(loc="best")
        fig.savefig("{}.png".format(self.symbol+"_"+str(self.n_days)), bbox_inches="tight")
        
        #Show the results
        print "MAPE on the testing data set: {}".format(mape_test)
        print
        print "Sharpe Ratio of Portfolio Values: {}".format(sharpe_ratio)
        print "Sharpe Ratio of {} Stock Prices: {}".format(self.symbol, sharpe_ratio_symbol)
        print
        print "Cumulative Return of Portfolio Values: {}".format(cum_ret)
        print "Cumulative Return of {} Stock Prices: {}".format(self.symbol, cum_ret_symbol)
        print
        print "Standard Deviation of Portfolio Values: {}".format(std_daily_ret)
        print "Standard Deviation of {} Stock Prices: {}".format(self.symbol, std_daily_ret_symbol)
        print
        print "Average Daily Return of Portfolio Values: {}".format(avg_daily_ret)
        print "Average Daily Return of {} Stock Prices: {}".format(self.symbol, avg_daily_ret_symbol)
        print

Next, we will use the class TradeStock() to conduct 3 case studies. These 3 case studies focus on Google, Apple and IBM's stock prices respectively. For different stocks, the training date range and the testing date range are different. The studies are illustrated in detail as follows.

2.1 Case Study 1: Google¶

In this study, we will investigate the performance of our regression models and trading strategy on Google stock price.

Training date range: 01/01/2011-12/31/2014
Testing date range: 01/01/2015-12/31/2015
Attempts of Prediction Interval: 5, 10 and 20 trading days respectively.

For each choice of prediction interval, we compute and return the MAPE of the final regression model on validation set in the training phase (done by the method get_best_learner() in BestLearner class). The prediction interval corresponds to the minimum MAPE will be used in the testing study. Firstly, the predictions will be made on testing date range, and will be compared with the actual price in terms of MAPE and plot. Secondly, a trading strategy is made based on the predictions. We will used this trading strategy to trade Google stock during the testing date range. Thirdly, according to the orders we make by the trading strategy, the portfolio values of the days during the testing date range are computed. And we compute the cumulative return, daily returns and sharpe ratio of the portfolio values. Finally, we use the Google stock price during the testing date range as the benchmark. The cumulative return, daily returns and sharpe ratio of the Google stock prices are computed to compare with those of portfolio values, and to evaluate if our trading strategy built based on regression model can beat the Google stock market.

First of all, we iinitialize the date ranges, stock symboel, prediction intervals and the objects of TradeStock class.

Also, our trading strategy beats the stock price in terms of both cumulative return and Sharpe ration. Having the start value of 100000 USD at the begining of year 2014, if we use our trading strategy to trade IBM stock, we can make over 10.14% profit at the end of the year 2014. On the other hand, if we don't use any trading strategy, and just buy IBM stock using all the 100000 USD at the begining of 2014, and hold the shares all year, we would lose about 11.4% value of our total value. Also, the higher Sharpe ratio of our portfolio values indicates that our trading strategy has lower risk than just holding the stock. From the second plot, we can see that our normalized portfolio value is bigger than the normalized stock price at most of the days in the testing date range. In another word, our trading strategy not only beats the market at the end of the year 2014, but also beats the market almost every day through the year 2014.

2.4 Conclusion¶

Three case studies are conducted. The results showed that our stock price predictor performs consistently well on these three different testing sets. In both Google and IBM studies, the MAPEs of the predictor on testing sets are both below 3%, which means that the predicted stock value 5 days out is within +/- 3% of actual value on average. In the study of Apple, the MAPE on testing set is about 6%, which is just a slightly above 5%. The predictor can successfully predict the trend in all the three case studies.

In all the three cases, the trading strategy based on the predictions by our stock price predictor overcomes the stock market in terms of cumulative return. Using our trading strategy can earn more profit or lose less money than just buy the stock and simply hold it for all the 3 cases. Also, our strategy has less risk than the just holding the stock in terms of higher Sharpe ratio in both of the Google and IBM studies.

In summary, we have shown that our stock price predictor and corresponding trading strategy have consistently good performances on different testing sets.
